WEBVTT

00:06.658 --> 00:08.921
Okay.

00:08.965 --> 00:11.402
Hi.
I'm Ignatius.

00:11.446 --> 00:13.448
Nope.
It's pretentious.

00:13.491 --> 00:14.449
I, uh--

00:14.492 --> 00:16.712
hey, my friends call me Iggs.

00:16.755 --> 00:19.149
No, they don't.
Dr. Igg--Dr. Iggs.

00:19.193 --> 00:21.021
[chuckles and groans]

00:21.064 --> 00:22.761
Okay.
Hey, I'm Ignatius.

00:22.805 --> 00:24.937
Dr. Iggs.
I'm Iggy.

00:24.981 --> 00:26.287
And would you please kill me?

00:26.330 --> 00:28.767
Uh, hi, my name is Iggy,

00:28.811 --> 00:30.334
and I am in hell.

00:30.378 --> 00:34.034
Oh, my God, stop,
stop, stop, stop.

00:34.077 --> 00:36.514
Just--hey, hi.

00:36.558 --> 00:38.299
Hey.

00:38.342 --> 00:39.604
Hey, you know what I am?

00:39.648 --> 00:40.388
I'm a psychiatrist.

00:40.431 --> 00:42.825
<i>[upbeat jazz music]</i>

00:42.868 --> 00:46.002
I'm a psychiatrist.

00:46.046 --> 00:47.047
<i>♪</i>

00:47.090 --> 00:48.135
Oh.
Hey, there.

00:48.178 --> 00:50.746
<i>♪</i>

00:50.789 --> 00:54.097
[items clattering]

00:54.141 --> 00:57.535
Some might call me
a textbook Scorpio.

00:57.579 --> 00:59.102
Watch out.

00:59.146 --> 01:01.800
I would say a sense of humor
is the most important thing.

01:01.844 --> 01:05.543
Communication
is the most important thing.

01:05.587 --> 01:08.590
Patience is the most
important thing?

01:08.633 --> 01:10.505
<i>♪</i>

01:10.548 --> 01:11.506
No.

01:13.160 --> 01:15.727
Hi, my name is Iggy,

01:15.771 --> 01:19.557
I am going through a divorce,
I have four amazing children,

01:19.601 --> 01:22.691
and I'm on this app because--

01:22.734 --> 01:25.911
well, because who wants
to go through this awful,

01:25.955 --> 01:29.176
confusing, joyous world alone?

01:29.219 --> 01:31.221
<i>[sighs]</i>

01:31.265 --> 01:34.181
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

01:34.224 --> 01:36.618
<i>♪</i>

01:36.661 --> 01:38.924
Yeah.

01:38.968 --> 01:42.667
<i>♪</i>

01:42.711 --> 01:43.929
All right.

01:43.973 --> 01:50.849
<i>♪</i>

01:53.722 --> 01:54.940
<i>[phone chimes]</i>

01:54.984 --> 01:57.073
[chuckles softly]

01:57.117 --> 02:02.209
<i>♪</i>

02:05.995 --> 02:07.127
[bell rings]

02:07.170 --> 02:09.564
Good morning.

02:09.607 --> 02:11.348
- [mouthing words]
- Morning.

02:11.392 --> 02:13.307
<i>[upbeat jazz music]</i>

02:13.350 --> 02:16.092
<i>♪</i>

02:16.136 --> 02:19.095
[mouthing words]

02:19.139 --> 02:26.189
<i>♪</i>

02:32.021 --> 02:35.242
[bell rings]

02:35.285 --> 02:38.027
Yeah, oh, yeah, I'll--bye.

02:38.070 --> 02:40.160
[bell rings]

02:40.203 --> 02:42.118
I mean, I just--
tell me honestly.

02:42.162 --> 02:43.424
Am I too old to date on an app?

02:43.467 --> 02:44.990
I'm not worried about
you meeting somebody.

02:45.034 --> 02:46.383
I am worried about you

02:46.427 --> 02:48.298
marrying the first guy
you date, all right?

02:48.342 --> 02:49.778
So let's cross that bridge
when we get there.

02:49.821 --> 02:51.171
All right, don't--don't
let me do that, by the way.

02:51.214 --> 02:52.781
Well, listen.

02:52.824 --> 02:54.304
It's just like my mom always
said when I was with Edie.

02:54.348 --> 02:58.221
There are plenty
of fish in the... sea.

02:58.265 --> 02:59.657
That was weird.

02:59.701 --> 03:02.182
Iggy, this is my father, Horace.

03:02.225 --> 03:04.662
- Oh.
- Dad, this is Iggy.

03:04.706 --> 03:06.316
Yeah, hi.
Nice to meet you, finally.

03:06.360 --> 03:07.970
I'm Iggy. Pleasure.

03:08.013 --> 03:10.320
All right, then.
Come on, we're going fishing.

03:10.364 --> 03:13.671
Today?
Wait. Now?

03:13.715 --> 03:15.847
The bass will be
sleeping by noon.

03:15.891 --> 03:18.198
[chuckling] I--I can't.
I'm at work.

03:18.241 --> 03:19.721
I'm working.

03:19.764 --> 03:22.811
I'm supervising a resident's
fem-pop bypass this morning.

03:22.854 --> 03:26.336
There's got to be other
doctors in this hospital.

03:26.380 --> 03:29.557
That is true.

03:29.600 --> 03:31.689
I'm sorry, Dad, this is
not how I run my department.

03:31.733 --> 03:33.604
This is not about how
you run your department.

03:33.648 --> 03:38.914
It's about how
you run your life.

03:38.957 --> 03:43.266
I can't.
I'm sorry.

03:43.310 --> 03:45.399
Well, suit yourself.

03:45.442 --> 03:50.360
But don't tell me I didn't try.

03:50.404 --> 03:51.883
What are you doing?
You wanted this, right?

03:51.927 --> 03:54.495
No, not like that.
Not out of the blue.

03:54.538 --> 03:58.281
You can't control
how love comes into your life.

03:58.325 --> 04:00.283
All right?
That's good advice for me, too.

04:00.327 --> 04:02.198
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

04:02.242 --> 04:04.505
[sighs] Okay.

04:04.548 --> 04:07.247
Hey, Pop, wait up. Hey.

04:07.290 --> 04:09.292
<i>[soft upbeat music]</i>

04:09.336 --> 04:11.860
Whoo-hoo.
That's what I'm talking about.

04:11.903 --> 04:16.865
<i>♪</i>

04:16.908 --> 04:19.868
Hey, good morning.
New haircut?

04:19.911 --> 04:22.349
Look, I know Casey
is out of town,

04:22.392 --> 04:24.176
so you need someone
to gossip with,

04:24.220 --> 04:26.744
but may I suggest,
quite literally,

04:26.788 --> 04:28.616
anyone else
in our entire department?

04:28.659 --> 04:30.748
Ooh, speaking
of our department,

04:30.792 --> 04:32.620
Layla's visa finally
got approved,

04:32.663 --> 04:34.317
which means, drum roll please.

04:34.361 --> 04:35.753
No.

04:35.797 --> 04:36.928
she's finally moving
out of my apartment

04:36.972 --> 04:38.321
and into her own place.

04:38.365 --> 04:40.454
You know, maybe you can
call Casey, FaceTime him?

04:40.497 --> 04:41.585
I don't know.

04:41.629 --> 04:42.934
All that's left to do now

04:42.978 --> 04:44.893
is to pick up my clothes
from storage,

04:44.936 --> 04:47.809
which I am dreading,
but I need them, you know?

04:47.852 --> 04:50.420
I've been living in the same
eight outfits for months

04:50.464 --> 04:54.119
and my undies are
practically translucent.

04:54.163 --> 04:55.773
Why did you wait till
things were see-through?

04:55.817 --> 04:57.035
I mean,
most storage places let you

04:57.079 --> 04:58.341
get things whenever you want.

04:58.385 --> 05:01.736
Yeah, well, it's not
that kind of storage.

05:05.522 --> 05:10.614
Brunstetter, a word?

05:10.658 --> 05:11.920
What are you doing?

05:11.963 --> 05:13.138
She can't afford her
blood pressure meds,

05:13.182 --> 05:14.836
and it's only 40 bucks, so--

05:14.879 --> 05:16.664
Okay, we don't pay
patients out of pocket.

05:16.707 --> 05:17.665
I know.

05:17.708 --> 05:20.102
Even in situations
like this.

05:20.145 --> 05:22.496
For every Esther, there are
a dozen more just like her.

05:22.539 --> 05:25.020
I know, it's just--

05:25.063 --> 05:28.153
it's hard not to do
something when I can.

05:28.197 --> 05:31.069
[indistinct chatter]

05:43.038 --> 05:45.997
You can pick up your
prescription at a pharmacy.

05:46.041 --> 05:47.347
Thank you.

05:47.390 --> 05:48.652
You really didn't need
to do this.

05:48.696 --> 05:50.437
It's okay.
It's not a problem at all.

05:50.480 --> 05:51.916
<i>[funky upbeat music]</i>

05:51.960 --> 05:54.092
Oh, hang on.
Just a little problem here.

05:54.136 --> 05:57.008
Sorry, guys, I'm just
a little short on cash.

05:57.052 --> 06:00.316
Oh, Max, Max.
Do you mind spotting me?

06:00.360 --> 06:03.580
Oh, sure.

06:03.624 --> 06:05.234
Happy to help.

06:05.277 --> 06:06.409
[whispers]
Sorry. Thank you.

06:06.453 --> 06:07.715
Mm-hmm.

06:07.758 --> 06:09.325
Let me guess.
Budget meeting?

06:09.369 --> 06:12.676
Oh, this is my new and
improved cost savings plan.

06:12.720 --> 06:14.025
Worked all week
on this bad boy.

06:14.069 --> 06:15.462
All right, how much
are you going to save?

06:15.505 --> 06:18.682
$432.

06:18.726 --> 06:20.162
Ooh, that's going
to be good meeting.

06:20.205 --> 06:21.511
Well hey, you just had
to borrow 5 bucks from me.

06:21.555 --> 06:23.165
You're not one to talk.

06:23.208 --> 06:24.471
All right, do you know what?

06:24.514 --> 06:25.863
You had to spot me because

06:25.907 --> 06:27.256
my patient couldn't afford
her blood pressure meds,

06:27.299 --> 06:29.301
and since it took
just 40 bucks to save her life,

06:29.345 --> 06:30.955
that is what I did.
- Hmm.

06:30.999 --> 06:33.523
And we see patients like
her every single day, Max,

06:33.567 --> 06:35.220
stuck in the
Medicare donut hole,

06:35.264 --> 06:36.657
unable to afford their meds.

06:36.700 --> 06:39.703
I mean, some of them can't
even afford a daily meal.

06:39.747 --> 06:42.140
I mean, if they had just
a little extra cash,

06:42.184 --> 06:44.795
they wouldn't keep
ending up in the ED.

06:44.839 --> 06:47.972
<i>[soft energetic music]</i>

06:48.016 --> 06:50.845
<i>♪</i>

06:50.888 --> 06:52.934
All right, well, that was not
the reaction I was expecting.

06:52.977 --> 06:56.067
But that is a great
savings plan, Lauren.

06:56.111 --> 06:57.373
Oh, no.

06:57.417 --> 06:58.722
<i>♪</i>

06:58.766 --> 07:00.724
This is Canaan Ochoa,
thrown from vehicle.

07:00.768 --> 07:02.857
Abrasions, hemothorax,
and crush injury

07:02.900 --> 07:04.511
to the right shoulder
and rib cage.

07:04.554 --> 07:06.077
[groaning]

07:06.121 --> 07:08.515
Give me a rapid infuser
and notify the blood bank.

07:08.558 --> 07:10.734
Prepare for rapid
sequence intubation.

07:10.778 --> 07:12.736
Make sure we have a humeral
head retractor in the kit.

07:12.780 --> 07:14.521
It's extensive crush injury.

07:14.564 --> 07:16.827
All spreaders and gougers
on the tray.

07:16.871 --> 07:20.265
On my count, one, two, three.

07:20.309 --> 07:23.312
- [groans]
- [indistinct]

07:23.355 --> 07:25.401
Work up that MAYSI score.

07:25.445 --> 07:27.403
Blood bank's been notified. <i>
[monitors beeping]</i>

07:27.447 --> 07:29.013
[groaning]

07:29.057 --> 07:31.407
It's probably
gonna require a drain.

07:31.451 --> 07:34.149
Problem looks too extensive
for a transhumeral procedure.

07:34.192 --> 07:36.543
Can you feel that?

07:36.586 --> 07:37.935
No.

07:37.979 --> 07:40.503
Anticipate a shoulder disarticulation.

07:40.547 --> 07:42.374
All right, what about now?

07:42.418 --> 07:44.507
Anything?

07:44.551 --> 07:46.944
What's wrong with me?

07:46.988 --> 07:48.598
<i>♪</i>

07:48.642 --> 07:50.600
The accident
crushed your shoulder.

07:50.644 --> 07:52.820
Your bones, muscles,
nerves, blood vessels,

07:52.863 --> 07:54.648
they're all badly damaged.

07:54.691 --> 07:56.084
Oh, my God.

07:56.127 --> 07:58.173
Determine if the patient
is a candidate for--

07:58.216 --> 08:00.697
All right,
we can save your life, Canaan,

08:00.741 --> 08:02.743
but the operation
is going to require

08:02.786 --> 08:05.397
the amputation
of your right arm.

08:05.441 --> 08:06.877
W-what?

08:06.921 --> 08:10.881
No, you can't take my arm.
Please, please.

08:10.925 --> 08:12.535
The artery in your shoulder,
it's been weakened.

08:12.579 --> 08:14.145
It could rupture at any second.

08:14.189 --> 08:16.626
If that happens,
you will die within minutes.

08:16.670 --> 08:17.932
We need to operate now.

08:17.975 --> 08:21.501
No, no, there has
to be some other way.

08:21.544 --> 08:22.980
I wish that there were.

08:23.024 --> 08:25.417
Well, don't I have
kind of say in this?

08:25.461 --> 08:26.636
Of course.

08:26.680 --> 08:27.942
We need your permission
to operate.

08:27.985 --> 08:29.552
Okay, well,
you don't have it.

08:29.596 --> 08:32.033
<i>[soft tense music]</i>

08:32.076 --> 08:33.556
<i>♪</i>

08:33.600 --> 08:39.170
You can't take my arm.
I'd rather die.

08:39.214 --> 08:45.873
<i>♪</i>

08:54.534 --> 08:57.275
Wow, we made good time.

08:57.319 --> 09:00.365
This is really something.
[laughs]

09:00.409 --> 09:03.281
Never been out here before.

09:03.325 --> 09:06.110
- Here, hold this.
- All right.

09:06.154 --> 09:08.896
- Want me to grab it?
- Nope.

09:08.939 --> 09:13.596
[birds singing]
- Wow.

09:13.640 --> 09:18.601
This is beautiful, Pops.
- [chuckles]

09:18.645 --> 09:21.604
It's just the two of us,
father and son,

09:21.648 --> 09:23.824
spending some good quality--
whoa, whoa, whoa.

09:23.867 --> 09:25.086
Where are you going?

09:25.129 --> 09:26.609
The best spot
is just down here.

09:26.653 --> 09:28.393
Yeah, but the sign.

09:28.437 --> 09:29.699
Oh, they got to put that up.

09:29.743 --> 09:31.745
Just making sure
we not terrorists out here

09:31.788 --> 09:34.704
trying to mess with the
New York City drinking water.

09:34.748 --> 09:36.053
It's nothing.

09:36.097 --> 09:39.448
Yeah, but it clearly
says no trespassing.

09:39.491 --> 09:42.059
You always mind the rules, Floyd.

09:42.103 --> 09:44.148
Good kid.

09:44.192 --> 09:46.237
Never too late to fix that.

09:46.281 --> 09:49.545
<i>[upbeat jazz music]</i>

09:49.589 --> 09:51.416
Oh, come on, now.

09:51.460 --> 09:55.638
It ain't fishing if you ain't
trespassing just a little.

09:55.682 --> 10:02.602
<i>♪</i>

10:03.690 --> 10:05.213
Yo, Pops, wait up.

10:05.256 --> 10:07.911
<i>♪</i>

10:08.564 --> 10:12.437
Hey, I got your page.
How can I help?

10:12.481 --> 10:15.266
My patient needs his right
arm amputated at the shoulder

10:15.310 --> 10:17.660
or he's going to be dead
within a matter of hours.

10:17.704 --> 10:20.620
However, he is refusing
the life-saving surgery,

10:20.663 --> 10:24.624
so I need you to
declare him incompetent

10:24.667 --> 10:26.669
so that I can move
forward with the operation

10:26.713 --> 10:29.367
and save his life.

10:29.411 --> 10:33.067
Okay,
do you know who that is?

10:33.110 --> 10:36.070
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

10:36.113 --> 10:38.681
- Who?
- That's Canaan Ochoa.

10:38.725 --> 10:43.599
He's the starting pitcher
for the Brooklyn Cyclones.

10:43.643 --> 10:48.560
<i>♪</i>

10:48.604 --> 10:49.649
Morning.

10:49.692 --> 10:50.693
Now, who's ready
to have their world

10:50.737 --> 10:52.739
completely rocked
by my new plan?

10:52.782 --> 10:54.610
Let's see,
your last cost-saving plan

10:54.654 --> 10:56.917
was equal to the price of
a one-way flight to Rochester.

10:56.960 --> 10:59.702
Well, then, buckle your
seatbelt, Madam Chairwoman.

10:59.746 --> 11:01.399
$5,000.

11:01.443 --> 11:03.445
That is the average cost

11:03.488 --> 11:05.229
when a patient
comes through our doors

11:05.273 --> 11:07.928
at this hospital,
but I have found a way

11:07.971 --> 11:13.411
to reduce this number to...

11:13.455 --> 11:15.109
50.

11:15.152 --> 11:17.677
Any questions?
- Yes, is this a joke?

11:17.720 --> 11:19.853
Nope, there's nothing funny
about savings like these.

11:19.896 --> 11:21.115
There's no way this is legal.

11:21.158 --> 11:22.333
Well,
that's a great question,

11:22.377 --> 11:23.639
and I'm glad you asked.

11:23.683 --> 11:25.641
We're going to accomplish this
with targeted

11:25.685 --> 11:28.296
monetary prescriptions
specifically designed

11:28.339 --> 11:30.907
to nip expensive
and avoidable hospital stays

11:30.951 --> 11:32.126
right in the bud.

11:32.169 --> 11:34.258
This expression you see?
Disbelief.

11:34.302 --> 11:36.478
Oh, okay.
Well, let me prove it to you.

11:36.521 --> 11:39.699
Fund a one-day pilot program,
and if it succeeds,

11:39.742 --> 11:41.091
we make it permanent

11:41.135 --> 11:45.705
and we sit back
and we let the savings roll in.

11:45.748 --> 11:47.489
<i>♪</i>

11:47.532 --> 11:50.274
It's hard to argue
with those numbers.

11:50.318 --> 11:53.103
Yeah, she's right,
so let's not argue.

11:53.147 --> 11:55.323
[pen clicking]

11:55.366 --> 11:59.196
All right, fine.
All in favor?

11:59.240 --> 12:01.938
<i>♪</i>

12:01.982 --> 12:05.725
Your pilot program
is hereby approved.

12:05.768 --> 12:06.987
Thank you, Karen.

12:07.030 --> 12:10.077
[indistinct chatter]
- [sighs]

12:10.120 --> 12:12.775
You mind showing me
how you plan on implementing

12:12.819 --> 12:15.299
this revolutionary,
never-been-thought-of program

12:15.343 --> 12:17.911
in just one day?

12:17.954 --> 12:19.782
I thought you'd never ask.

12:19.826 --> 12:22.785
<i>[soft upbeat music]</i>

12:22.829 --> 12:26.528
<i>♪</i>

12:26.571 --> 12:29.009
This is going to change lives.

12:29.052 --> 12:31.446
<i>♪</i>

12:31.489 --> 12:34.144
Oh, dear God.

12:34.188 --> 12:37.278
<i>[heart monitor beeping]</i>

12:38.583 --> 12:41.151
[door opens and closes]

12:41.195 --> 12:44.851
Hi.
Mr. Ochoa?

12:44.894 --> 12:46.635
Hi, I'm Dr. Frome.

12:46.678 --> 12:49.203
Can I ask you a few questions?

12:49.246 --> 12:51.335
[sighs]
Do what you got to do.

12:51.379 --> 12:52.597
Okay, thank you.

12:52.641 --> 12:54.208
Can you tell me
what year it is?

12:54.251 --> 12:56.210
2022.

12:56.253 --> 12:58.342
And where are we right now?

12:58.386 --> 13:00.475
A hospital.

13:00.518 --> 13:03.957
And if you found
a stamped letter on the ground,

13:04.000 --> 13:06.220
what would you do with it?

13:06.263 --> 13:09.353
You think I'm crazy.

13:09.397 --> 13:12.879
You have rejected
life-saving medical care,

13:12.922 --> 13:15.533
and it is my job to determine
whether you're of sound mind

13:15.577 --> 13:17.231
to sign your death warrant today.

13:17.274 --> 13:20.190
That's not the kind of thing
that we want to get wrong,

13:20.234 --> 13:22.105
understand?

13:22.149 --> 13:24.020
[sighs]

13:24.064 --> 13:26.370
All right.

13:26.414 --> 13:27.981
Do you have any family
that would be impacted

13:28.024 --> 13:31.071
by your choice to die?

13:31.114 --> 13:34.422
No, my team was my family.

13:34.465 --> 13:37.294
I already lost them.

13:37.338 --> 13:39.993
You know,
many successful people

13:40.036 --> 13:42.212
have a brutally hard time
separating the sense of self

13:42.256 --> 13:43.561
from their career.

13:43.605 --> 13:45.563
T-this isn't my career.

13:45.607 --> 13:49.045
Okay, all right,
it's not your career.

13:49.089 --> 13:50.264
Got it.

13:50.307 --> 13:53.833
So tell me, what is it?

13:53.876 --> 13:56.444
This is my life.

13:56.487 --> 13:59.839
This is--I don't
even know the word.

13:59.882 --> 14:04.887
You're calling?

14:04.931 --> 14:07.585
You know the first game
I ever pitched?

14:07.629 --> 14:11.154
I left my body.
For real.

14:11.198 --> 14:14.418
I mean, I was up there just
thinking about all the things

14:14.462 --> 14:16.899
I had to do, you know,
move my ankle here,

14:16.943 --> 14:19.771
adjust my hips there.

14:19.815 --> 14:21.991
And then suddenly,
I was just...

14:22.035 --> 14:27.127
watching it all happen,
10,000 tiny movements,

14:27.170 --> 14:30.521
and then bam.

14:30.565 --> 14:35.048
That ball soared right to
where it was supposed to go,

14:35.091 --> 14:37.267
and it may have been
me doing the wind-up,

14:37.311 --> 14:39.530
but God was throwing that ball.

14:39.574 --> 14:41.924
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

14:41.968 --> 14:45.580
<i>♪</i>

14:45.623 --> 14:49.671
And if I can't have that...

14:49.714 --> 14:52.500
I don't want to live, man.

14:52.543 --> 14:55.503
<i>♪</i>

14:55.546 --> 14:57.853
I know what I'm choosing, doctor.

14:57.897 --> 15:01.248
<i>♪</i>

15:01.291 --> 15:05.339
So if I found a stamped
envelope on the ground,

15:05.382 --> 15:08.908
I'd mail it.

15:08.951 --> 15:14.609
<i>♪</i>

15:14.652 --> 15:17.525
[shakily takes deep breath]

15:17.568 --> 15:24.227
<i>♪</i>

15:24.271 --> 15:27.404
Cancel the surgery.

15:27.448 --> 15:29.885
<i>♪</i>

15:29.929 --> 15:31.234
<i>[siren wailing]</i>

15:31.278 --> 15:32.670
23-year-old jumper off
the Hell's Gate Bridge,

15:32.714 --> 15:34.542
now with multiple
lower extremity fractures.

15:34.585 --> 15:35.673
Heart rate,
respirations normal.

15:35.717 --> 15:36.979
We got to him
in the nick of time.

15:37.023 --> 15:39.460
Stay with us, kid.
We got you.

15:39.503 --> 15:41.375
<i>[soft tense music]</i>

15:41.418 --> 15:43.812
I messed up.
I'm sorry.

15:43.855 --> 15:45.335
Okay, let's get him
to Bay 29.

15:45.379 --> 15:46.423
You got nothing
to be sorry about.

15:46.467 --> 15:47.598
Just promise us once
they fix you up,

15:47.642 --> 15:48.991
you'll come by the station
and say hi.

15:49.035 --> 15:50.819
Patient ortho and psych, stat.

15:50.862 --> 15:53.213
- Mike?
- [gasping]

15:53.256 --> 15:56.172
Mike?
Man down!

15:56.216 --> 15:57.869
Any medical history
I should know about?

15:57.913 --> 15:59.523
No, nothing.
Mike's in perfect health.

15:59.567 --> 16:01.003
He's the one
who saved the jumper.

16:01.047 --> 16:03.005
- We need a stretcher!
- I'm on it.

16:03.049 --> 16:06.095
[gasping]

16:11.622 --> 16:14.451
<i>[Aloe Blacc's
"I Need A Dollar"]</i>

16:14.495 --> 16:16.714
<i>♪</i>

16:16.758 --> 16:18.499
Wow, it really works.

16:18.542 --> 16:20.153
What are you going to
spend your prescription on?

16:20.196 --> 16:21.589
Oh, my knees are terrible.

16:21.632 --> 16:22.851
I'm a waiter, but I
haven't been able to work,

16:22.894 --> 16:25.114
so I'm getting orthotics.

16:25.158 --> 16:26.811
Great.

16:26.855 --> 16:28.030
<i>♪</i>

16:28.074 --> 16:29.249
There you go.
Help yourself.

16:29.292 --> 16:30.250
Who's next?

16:30.772 --> 16:31.991
Hi, there.

16:32.034 --> 16:33.731
Pop that in,
and there's your cash.

16:33.775 --> 16:35.211
<i>♪ A dollar is what I need</i>

16:35.255 --> 16:36.517
What are you going to
spend your prescription on?

16:36.560 --> 16:38.475
- Groceries.
- Excellent.

16:38.519 --> 16:40.782
<i>- ♪ A dollar is what I need
- ♪ Hey, hey</i>

16:40.825 --> 16:42.305
[softly] It's working.

16:42.349 --> 16:44.177
<i>♪ A dollar, a dollar,
a dollar is what I need ♪</i>

16:44.220 --> 16:46.570
- A gym membership.
- Nice.

16:46.614 --> 16:48.050
<i>♪ And if I share with you
my story ♪</i>

16:48.094 --> 16:50.052
<i>♪ Would you
share your dollar with me ♪</i>

16:50.096 --> 16:51.532
<i>♪ Come on,
share your dollar with me ♪</i>

16:51.575 --> 16:54.404
A haircut.

16:54.448 --> 16:55.753
Good.

16:55.797 --> 16:57.755
<i>♪ Come on,
share your dollar with me ♪</i>

16:57.799 --> 17:00.236
Tickets to the Laugh Shack.

17:00.280 --> 17:01.237
Mm.

17:03.109 --> 17:06.242
<i>[machine beeping]</i>

17:08.549 --> 17:12.901
Uh, I was prescribed cash
for a bus pass.

17:12.944 --> 17:14.903
Walking to work in this heat

17:14.946 --> 17:17.253
was triggering
my extreme asthma.

17:17.297 --> 17:22.780
Yeah, that's--may I try?
Hmm.

17:22.824 --> 17:25.914
<i>[machine beeping]</i>

17:30.179 --> 17:32.181
I think this well has run dry.

17:32.225 --> 17:35.489
Sorry, this was only
a pilot program.

17:35.532 --> 17:39.493
So this prescription
is no longer any good?

17:39.536 --> 17:42.496
<i>[downbeat music]</i>

17:42.539 --> 17:49.068
<i>♪</i>

17:51.461 --> 17:54.464
This time, jig it a little
when you reel it back.

17:54.508 --> 17:56.510
I never knew you
liked fishing this much.

17:56.553 --> 17:59.121
[chuckles]
Ever since I was a kid.

18:02.516 --> 18:04.866
Oh, don't watch me,
watch the rod tip.

18:06.041 --> 18:10.001
Rod tip. Right.
[chuckles]

18:10.045 --> 18:12.439
[sighs]
- Oh, not like that.

18:12.482 --> 18:15.137
You try to hook them,
not tickle them.

18:15.181 --> 18:17.313
Hey, man, you never
taught me how to fish.

18:17.357 --> 18:19.228
How am I supposed to know
what I'm doing out here?

18:19.272 --> 18:21.274
Yeah, I never taught you
how to be a surgeon neither,

18:21.317 --> 18:23.363
and that turned out just fine.

18:30.152 --> 18:33.155
[ratchet clicking]
- Oh, Pops, I got something.

18:33.199 --> 18:35.853
Wait, what--what do I do?

18:35.897 --> 18:37.986
Run!

18:38.029 --> 18:39.770
What?

18:39.814 --> 18:41.642
<i>[upbeat jazz music]</i>

18:41.685 --> 18:42.947
Oh, crap!

18:42.991 --> 18:44.819
<i>[indistinct radio chatter]</i>

18:44.862 --> 18:46.429
Son of a--

18:46.473 --> 18:52.609
<i>♪</i>

18:53.741 --> 18:55.177
Lungs are clear.

18:55.221 --> 18:57.353
- Regular heart rhythm.
- EKG looks fine.

18:57.397 --> 18:59.094
Pupils reactive,
no signs of head trauma.

18:59.138 --> 19:00.182
So it's not cardiac.

19:00.226 --> 19:02.097
It's probably not subdural.

19:02.141 --> 19:03.620
[gasping]

19:03.664 --> 19:05.231
- No signs of concussion.
- No signs of bleeding.

19:05.274 --> 19:06.710
It doesn't make any sense.

19:06.754 --> 19:08.538
Mike was fine before
he went in the water.

19:08.582 --> 19:09.800
He didn't even hesitate.

19:09.844 --> 19:12.847
He dove right in
and pulled the guy to shore.

19:12.890 --> 19:14.240
He's dry drowning.

19:14.283 --> 19:15.850
But there's no water
in his lungs.

19:15.893 --> 19:17.199
He must have inhaled

19:17.243 --> 19:18.679
some small particles
when he dove into the river.

19:18.722 --> 19:20.768
His airway is blocked
due to severe laryngeal spasm.

19:20.811 --> 19:22.161
We can't oxygenate him.

19:22.204 --> 19:23.249
There's no air
that's getting in.

19:23.292 --> 19:25.555
No, we need to intubate now.
Come on.

19:25.599 --> 19:27.688
[gasping]

19:27.731 --> 19:29.907
<i>[soft tense music]</i>

19:29.951 --> 19:31.909
If one of your
patients told you

19:31.953 --> 19:34.608
that they were going
to go home and hang themselves,

19:34.651 --> 19:35.609
wouldn't you stop them?

19:35.652 --> 19:36.871
That's not the same thing.

19:36.914 --> 19:38.220
Mental health
care professionals

19:38.264 --> 19:40.222
intervene if someone
demonstrates a plan.

19:40.266 --> 19:42.659
If a patient is actively
going to pursue self-harm,

19:42.703 --> 19:43.921
yes, of course, I step in.

19:43.965 --> 19:45.706
But Canaan
isn't doing anything.

19:45.749 --> 19:49.449
He's just refusing to let us do
something, which is his right.

19:49.492 --> 19:51.929
Don't hide behind semantics.
Let's call this what it is.

19:51.973 --> 19:53.409
We are letting him die.

19:53.453 --> 19:54.584
No, we are not.

19:54.628 --> 19:55.977
We are letting a patient
tell the doctors

19:56.020 --> 19:58.022
what they can
and can't do to his body.

19:58.066 --> 19:59.241
That's it.

19:59.285 --> 20:00.155
That's what New Amsterdam
stands for.

20:00.199 --> 20:01.591
That's why we're here.

20:01.635 --> 20:02.853
Really?

20:02.897 --> 20:05.204
I thought that we were
here to save lives.

20:05.247 --> 20:07.815
No, no, not against a
patient's wishes, we're not.

20:07.858 --> 20:09.904
Even if that was ethically
okay, which it is not,

20:09.947 --> 20:12.950
he would sue you for
wrongful life and he would win.

20:12.994 --> 20:15.257
Believe me.

20:15.301 --> 20:17.128
If you force a surgery
on that man,

20:17.172 --> 20:18.565
you will lose your license.

20:18.608 --> 20:22.133
You will never
practice medicine again.

20:22.177 --> 20:23.483
Is that what you want?

20:23.526 --> 20:30.446
<i>♪</i>

20:35.669 --> 20:37.497
Prep Canaan Ochoa
for surgery.

20:37.540 --> 20:44.460
<i>♪</i>

20:51.554 --> 20:51.772
<i>...</i>

20:51.815 --> 20:54.644
<i>[soft tense music]</i>

20:54.688 --> 20:56.820
Why are you doing this?

20:56.864 --> 20:58.300
[mouthing words]

20:58.344 --> 20:59.649
The subclavian artery
could rupture at any moment.

20:59.693 --> 21:03.262
We don't have much time
to save this man's life.

21:03.305 --> 21:05.786
<i>♪</i>

21:05.829 --> 21:08.615
You can start.

21:08.658 --> 21:13.097
<i>♪</i>

21:13.141 --> 21:14.925
Ah--

21:14.969 --> 21:16.971
I don't want
to live like this.

21:17.014 --> 21:24.195
<i>♪</i>

21:24.500 --> 21:26.502
Out!

21:28.374 --> 21:31.202
Everybody out.
Clear the OR.

21:31.246 --> 21:32.769
[sniffles]

21:32.813 --> 21:35.685
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

21:35.729 --> 21:42.692
<i>♪</i>

21:58.142 --> 22:01.232
You offend me.

22:01.276 --> 22:02.495
Would you tell a group
of wounded vets

22:02.538 --> 22:05.672
that their lives
aren't worth living?

22:05.715 --> 22:08.196
Or someone who is missing
an eye or a leg?

22:08.239 --> 22:11.895
I-i-it's not that.

22:11.939 --> 22:13.593
Then what?

22:13.636 --> 22:16.596
You're not special anymore,
so you're just going to die?

22:16.639 --> 22:20.208
<i>♪</i>

22:20.251 --> 22:21.731
[sighs weakly]

22:21.775 --> 22:25.169
I'm nothing else.

22:25.213 --> 22:30.871
Before baseball, I was nothing.

22:30.914 --> 22:35.310
And now, without it...

22:35.354 --> 22:37.225
what's left?

22:37.268 --> 22:43.753
<i>♪</i>

22:43.797 --> 22:47.409
If I had quit when
I couldn't see a way forward,

22:47.453 --> 22:50.847
I would not be here
with you now.

22:50.891 --> 22:53.284
You have spent your whole
life defining yourself

22:53.328 --> 22:54.938
in this one narrow way,

22:54.982 --> 22:58.202
and you have convinced yourself
that is poetry.

22:58.246 --> 23:03.294
<i>♪</i>

23:03.338 --> 23:05.775
I got news for you, Canaan.

23:05.819 --> 23:10.954
You would not be any less human
if you woke up in post-op.

23:10.998 --> 23:13.304
<i>♪</i>

23:13.348 --> 23:17.221
In fact, maybe,

23:17.265 --> 23:21.138
I don't know, just maybe,

23:21.182 --> 23:23.619
you would be more.

23:23.663 --> 23:26.056
[sniffles]

23:26.100 --> 23:27.971
[sighs]

23:28.015 --> 23:31.148
<i>♪</i>

23:31.192 --> 23:32.541
[chuckles]

23:32.585 --> 23:35.762
Boy, you should have
seen the look on your face.

23:35.805 --> 23:38.852
You got wheels, son,
I'll give you that.

23:38.895 --> 23:40.288
You think this is funny?

23:40.331 --> 23:42.464
Come on, we made a
rent-a-cop run a little.

23:42.508 --> 23:44.466
Man needed exercise.

23:44.510 --> 23:47.643
That was a Homeland Security
officer, Dad.

23:47.687 --> 23:49.732
Homeland Security,
for God's sake.

23:49.776 --> 23:51.212
Oh, you need to relax.

23:51.255 --> 23:52.474
I'm a doctor
at a public hospital.

23:52.518 --> 23:54.128
If I get detained
by Homeland Security,

23:54.171 --> 23:55.651
I could lose my license.

23:55.695 --> 23:57.610
Yeah, here we go with
the doctor business again.

23:57.653 --> 24:01.222
Every chance you get,
you slip that in.

24:01.265 --> 24:03.267
Spoons.
They like spoons.

24:03.311 --> 24:04.486
We're going to put spoons
on the end of this.

24:04.530 --> 24:07.010
What the hell are you doing?

24:07.054 --> 24:10.057
What I came to do.
Fish are still biting.

24:10.100 --> 24:12.625
Come on, let's go.

24:12.668 --> 24:14.496
Are you serious right now?

24:14.540 --> 24:15.802
We could have gone to jail.

24:15.845 --> 24:17.281
No, we're not going fishing.
We're going home.

24:17.325 --> 24:19.588
You're the one pestering me
for months!

24:19.632 --> 24:21.503
You're the one
who wanted all this!

24:21.547 --> 24:22.896
And now, you're blaming me

24:22.939 --> 24:24.506
because it don't live up
to your high expectations.

24:24.550 --> 24:26.726
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

24:26.769 --> 24:28.292
That's--that's
not what this is.

24:28.336 --> 24:29.946
Nobody force you
to be here, Floyd.

24:29.990 --> 24:32.949
And last I checked,
nobody's keeping you here now.

24:32.993 --> 24:35.038
<i>♪</i>

24:35.082 --> 24:40.870
I came to go fishing, and
fishing is what I mean to do.

24:40.914 --> 24:46.485
<i>♪</i>

24:53.622 --> 24:57.060
How many nibbles
have we gotten?

24:57.104 --> 24:58.105
What?

24:58.148 --> 25:01.064
Likes, bites, hearts, swipes.

25:01.108 --> 25:02.892
And how many hot dudes are
buying what we are selling?

25:02.936 --> 25:04.851
Oh, my gosh,
Oh, the hot dudes.

25:04.894 --> 25:07.244
I don't know, let's see.

25:07.288 --> 25:10.204
All right.

25:10.247 --> 25:12.772
Uh, zero.

25:12.815 --> 25:14.817
Is that right?

25:14.861 --> 25:16.427
You know,
maybe it didn't post.

25:16.471 --> 25:18.212
No, no.
No, it posted.

25:18.255 --> 25:19.909
It's right there.
- Oh, yeah.

25:19.953 --> 25:21.911
Clear as day.

25:21.955 --> 25:26.742
I guess everyone who saw it
just swiped the other way.

25:26.786 --> 25:30.964
Turns out nobody's buying
what I'm selling today.

25:31.007 --> 25:32.443
Okay. Hmm.

25:32.487 --> 25:34.402
Oh.
[chuckles]

25:36.273 --> 25:37.448
Okay.

25:40.147 --> 25:41.844
For what it's worth,

25:41.888 --> 25:45.326
I would have swiped
the right direction.

25:47.328 --> 25:48.764
[chuckles softly]

25:48.808 --> 25:50.897
<i>[police siren wailing outside]</i>

25:50.940 --> 25:52.855
[phone clatters]

25:52.899 --> 25:54.161
[exhales deeply]

25:54.204 --> 25:55.292
<i>Big news, everybody.</i>

25:55.336 --> 25:56.598
Our humble,
little pilot program

25:56.642 --> 25:58.600
was an unmitigated success.

25:58.644 --> 26:01.342
Today, we saved this hospital,
conservatively speaking,

26:01.385 --> 26:04.475
$100,000.

26:04.519 --> 26:05.476
I know what you're thinking.

26:05.520 --> 26:06.652
That's maybe the first time

26:06.695 --> 26:08.567
I've actually
saved this hospital money.

26:08.610 --> 26:09.785
That's why I wanted
to get it in writing.

26:09.829 --> 26:11.744
Now, here's what I'm thinking.

26:11.787 --> 26:14.398
We redirect those savings right
back into the ATM in the lobby

26:14.442 --> 26:16.052
where there are still
patients lined up

26:16.096 --> 26:17.358
to fulfill their prescriptions

26:17.401 --> 26:19.578
and we just
keep that magic flowing.

26:19.621 --> 26:22.406
Some people thought
it couldn't be done.

26:22.450 --> 26:24.321
This is where
our money has been going?

26:24.365 --> 26:25.801
Pedicures?

26:25.845 --> 26:27.063
Prescribed by a podiatrist
for an ingrown toenail.

26:27.107 --> 26:28.499
The Laugh Shack?

26:28.543 --> 26:30.284
For depression.
Laughter is the best medicine.

26:30.327 --> 26:31.633
Seeds?

26:31.677 --> 26:33.200
Behavioral health
uses gardening

26:33.243 --> 26:34.331
to help ease anxiety.

26:34.375 --> 26:35.637
Lingerie?

26:35.681 --> 26:37.726
Support bras, actually.
It's a great story--

26:37.770 --> 26:40.860
We're a hospital, Max,
not a Target.

26:40.903 --> 26:41.904
Right.

26:41.948 --> 26:43.340
How do we know
these patients are

26:43.384 --> 26:45.821
even using the money for
what it was prescribed for?

26:45.865 --> 26:47.170
We don't.

26:47.214 --> 26:48.563
So any of these people
would just take our money

26:48.607 --> 26:50.609
and go out and buy
a PlayStation game?

26:50.652 --> 26:52.654
Yeah, actually,
that was prescribed

26:52.698 --> 26:54.264
for a patient with autism.

26:54.308 --> 26:56.005
Helps with social skills.

26:56.049 --> 26:59.356
Our detractors already
accuse socialized medicine

26:59.400 --> 27:00.662
of being just handouts.

27:00.706 --> 27:02.664
Now you're standing here

27:02.708 --> 27:04.623
saying your big innovation
is literally handouts?

27:04.666 --> 27:06.842
No, no, no, no.

27:06.886 --> 27:09.715
Our medical staff are
assessing patients' needs

27:09.758 --> 27:12.152
and then writing them
specific prescriptions--

27:12.195 --> 27:13.544
- For cash?
- Yeah.

27:13.588 --> 27:15.068
There's zero
accountability here, Max.

27:15.111 --> 27:16.678
Well, that line of thinking
suggests that you only

27:16.722 --> 27:19.159
see our patients as crooks
and liars when actually,

27:19.202 --> 27:22.553
they're just real people
in need of real health care.

27:22.597 --> 27:23.685
But none of these
things are health care.

27:23.729 --> 27:26.035
All of these things
are health care.

27:26.079 --> 27:29.212
A bus pass for a woman whose
severe asthma is triggered

27:29.256 --> 27:32.128
every time she's forced to walk
to work, that is health care.

27:32.172 --> 27:33.869
And when we spend money now,
we save money later,

27:33.913 --> 27:38.134
because all of this
is preventative care.

27:38.178 --> 27:41.877
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

27:41.921 --> 27:43.400
<i>♪</i>

27:43.444 --> 27:44.706
[sighs]
If you don't believe me,

27:44.750 --> 27:46.186
just follow these patients
for six weeks

27:46.229 --> 27:47.578
and you'll see that's true.

27:47.622 --> 27:49.668
Here's what will be true
today or in six weeks.

27:49.711 --> 27:51.495
You want New Amsterdam
to give away free money

27:51.539 --> 27:52.714
and no matter how you spin it,

27:52.758 --> 27:54.063
those are handouts
and that's just wrong.

27:54.107 --> 27:57.023
- No, Karen--
- I'm sorry, Max, shut it down.

27:57.066 --> 28:00.243
<i>♪</i>

28:00.287 --> 28:03.246
[indistinct chatter]

28:03.290 --> 28:07.947
<i>♪</i>

28:07.990 --> 28:10.253
<i>[medical equipment beeping]</i>

28:10.297 --> 28:13.430
He's progressed
to hemorrhagic pulmonary edema.

28:13.474 --> 28:14.997
BP is dropping.

28:15.041 --> 28:16.651
His heart's not getting
enough damn oxygen.

28:16.695 --> 28:19.262
- Hang another bag of saline.
- And start a dobutamine drip.

28:19.306 --> 28:20.960
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

28:21.003 --> 28:23.092
- It looks like V-fib.
- Damn it.

28:23.136 --> 28:25.442
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

28:25.486 --> 28:27.053
<i>[tense music]</i>

28:27.096 --> 28:30.447
<i>[electrical whirring]</i>
Confirming V-fib.

28:30.491 --> 28:31.622
<i>♪</i>

28:31.666 --> 28:33.059
Clear. <i>
[defibrillator thumps]</i>

28:33.102 --> 28:35.104
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

28:35.148 --> 28:36.279
Nothing.

28:36.323 --> 28:38.629
Going again. <i>
[electrical whirring]</i>

28:38.673 --> 28:39.718
Clear. <i>
[defibrillator thumps]</i>

28:39.761 --> 28:41.371
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

28:41.415 --> 28:42.677
Nothing.

28:42.721 --> 28:44.244
Going again.

28:44.287 --> 28:45.724
There's too much blunting.

28:45.767 --> 28:47.769
<i>[defibrillator whirring]</i>

28:47.813 --> 28:49.205
I can't get any oxygen in.

28:49.249 --> 28:52.731
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

28:52.774 --> 28:55.690
<i>[soft solemn music]</i>

28:55.734 --> 29:02.828
<i>♪</i>

29:04.612 --> 29:06.570
[sighs]

29:06.614 --> 29:09.965
Time of death, 4:22 p.m.

29:10.009 --> 29:16.798
<i>♪</i>

29:16.842 --> 29:19.932
<i>[EKG flatlining]</i>

29:32.553 --> 29:37.514
We did everything we could.

29:37.558 --> 29:40.343
But I just--

29:40.387 --> 29:44.173
<i>♪</i>

29:44.217 --> 29:46.001
I'm so sorry.

29:46.045 --> 29:48.351
<i>♪</i>

29:48.395 --> 29:50.527
[sighs shakily]

29:50.571 --> 29:57.752
<i>♪</i>

30:10.156 --> 30:12.898
<i>[upbeat jazz music]</i>

30:12.941 --> 30:14.856
<i>♪</i>

30:14.900 --> 30:17.206
Oh, my God.

30:17.250 --> 30:19.513
The fish won.
[laughs]

30:19.556 --> 30:22.342
Can't control
how love comes to you, huh?

30:22.385 --> 30:24.735
Aren't you supposed to
be a brilliant therapist,

30:24.779 --> 30:26.215
master of human insight?

30:26.259 --> 30:28.174
Oh, come on, it couldn't have
been that bad, right?

30:28.217 --> 30:30.698
Plus, you can't put a price
on adventure.

30:30.741 --> 30:31.960
Although to be fair,

30:32.004 --> 30:33.614
I don't know how much
those pants cost.

30:33.657 --> 30:36.399
I should have known playing
hooky with him was a mistake.

30:36.443 --> 30:38.662
To think all this time,
I got him to hang out with me,

30:38.706 --> 30:41.317
what, three,
maybe four times, max?

30:41.361 --> 30:43.667
And it's always me
trying to arrange it.

30:43.711 --> 30:45.931
It's always me trying
to pin him down.

30:45.974 --> 30:48.934
And there he was this morning
coming to me with a plan.

30:48.977 --> 30:51.240
All right?
And he was so excited.

30:51.284 --> 30:53.373
But you know what?

30:53.416 --> 30:55.462
He wasn't showing up for me.

30:55.505 --> 30:57.681
'Cause when I got in trouble,
he didn't care.

30:57.725 --> 30:58.944
Yeah.
You know what?

30:58.987 --> 31:01.076
I almost got arrested today.

31:01.120 --> 31:02.295
What?

31:02.338 --> 31:03.992
Yeah, almost lost
my whole career.

31:04.036 --> 31:07.648
And all he can think about was
getting back to the damn trout.

31:07.691 --> 31:11.695
And when I called him out
on it, he blew up.

31:11.739 --> 31:14.568
Dude went from Norman Rockwell
to screaming

31:14.611 --> 31:17.136
to total indifference
in one afternoon.

31:17.179 --> 31:20.356
Oh, sorry to hear that.

31:20.400 --> 31:23.359
Well, Mama was right.
She was right.

31:23.403 --> 31:25.318
She always said that horse
was like a roller coaster.

31:25.361 --> 31:27.233
Starts out fun,
but before you know it,

31:27.276 --> 31:29.496
your back's out
and you want to throw up.

31:29.539 --> 31:31.802
Hey, hey, hey, hey, what
was the car ride home like?

31:31.846 --> 31:33.848
I Ubered.

31:33.892 --> 31:38.374
You know why?
- Uh, why?

31:38.418 --> 31:41.029
'Cause he's still out there fishing.

31:44.206 --> 31:46.861
So what can you say
about a man like that?

31:46.905 --> 31:47.993
Well.

31:48.036 --> 31:50.343
No, go ahead, say it.

31:50.386 --> 31:54.390
Um, okay, well...

31:54.434 --> 31:56.175
I've known the man
for exactly two seconds,

31:56.218 --> 31:58.046
so this is worth
a grain of salt.

31:58.090 --> 32:02.703
But it sounds like
a textbook example

32:02.746 --> 32:06.011
of someone
with bipolar disorder.

32:06.054 --> 32:08.970
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

32:09.014 --> 32:12.931
<i>♪</i>

32:12.974 --> 32:15.890
<i>[indistinct PA announcement]</i>

32:15.934 --> 32:18.153
<i>♪</i>

32:18.197 --> 32:19.807
And it was working.

32:19.850 --> 32:23.071
I didn't come here today
to get a bus pass,

32:23.115 --> 32:24.855
I came for my asthma.

32:24.899 --> 32:28.163
Yeah, but all you needed
was the bus pass.

32:28.207 --> 32:29.904
[chuckles]

32:29.948 --> 32:32.646
Hang on, I can--

32:32.689 --> 32:34.387
[chuckles]

32:34.430 --> 32:36.693
I gave all my money away
this morning.

32:36.737 --> 32:39.218
<i>♪</i>

32:39.261 --> 32:45.006
Sorry, I couldn't help
but overhear.

32:45.050 --> 32:46.181
Here.
I got you, ma'am.

32:46.225 --> 32:50.969
- Oh, that's--
- Please.

32:51.012 --> 32:52.100
Thank you, dear.

32:52.144 --> 32:54.233
Happy to help.

32:54.276 --> 32:58.585
<i>♪</i>

32:58.628 --> 33:00.674
What is it with this place?

33:00.717 --> 33:03.938
You know, sometimes,
even I don't know.

33:03.982 --> 33:05.722
Excuse me.

33:05.766 --> 33:11.250
That was very kind,
but you didn't have to do that.

33:11.293 --> 33:12.599
Oh, my pleasure.

33:12.642 --> 33:14.166
I donate to charity
all the time,

33:14.209 --> 33:16.342
but nothing feels better

33:16.385 --> 33:18.170
than knowing exactly
who your money is helping.

33:18.213 --> 33:25.307
<i>♪</i>

33:25.873 --> 33:26.874
Hmm.

33:26.917 --> 33:33.837
<i>♪</i>

33:37.319 --> 33:38.712
Good work.

33:38.755 --> 33:41.976
Everyone, thank you all.
I know today was hard.

33:42.020 --> 33:43.934
<i>♪</i>

33:43.978 --> 33:46.676
You did the hard lift,
changing his mind.

33:46.720 --> 33:48.983
<i>♪</i>

33:49.027 --> 33:53.031
All I did was start
from a different perspective.

33:53.074 --> 34:00.168
<i>♪</i>

34:06.044 --> 34:10.004
- Good night.
- Hey, Karen, do me a favor.

34:10.048 --> 34:13.660
Define handout.
Humor me.

34:13.703 --> 34:16.489
[groans softly]
A gift you didn't earn.

34:16.532 --> 34:19.274
Something for nothing.

34:19.318 --> 34:22.625
So many people come here
needing our help

34:22.669 --> 34:25.019
and a lot of them can't pay,

34:25.063 --> 34:26.760
but is stopping an unhoused man

34:26.803 --> 34:29.328
from having a heart attack
a handout?

34:29.371 --> 34:32.592
Or giving an undocumented kid
a polio vaccine?

34:32.635 --> 34:34.463
It's not the same.
That's medicine.

34:34.507 --> 34:37.684
Everything I did today
was medicine.

34:37.727 --> 34:39.294
The board just can't see that.

34:39.338 --> 34:41.079
But fortunately,
I don't need the board

34:41.122 --> 34:43.603
to see that medicine
extends beyond these walls,

34:43.646 --> 34:48.912
because the rest of the world
already knows that.

34:48.956 --> 34:50.914
Okay, I'll bite.

34:50.958 --> 34:53.395
<i>[soft upbeat music]</i>

34:53.439 --> 34:56.006
"Sponsor a patient."
- Mm-hmm.

34:56.050 --> 34:58.966
Each of these patients only
needs a small amount of cash

34:59.009 --> 35:04.798
to make a huge impact
on their overall health.

35:04.841 --> 35:06.060
See?

35:06.104 --> 35:08.410
<i>♪ Nobody knows
how to go back home ♪</i>

35:08.454 --> 35:10.195
<i>♪</i>

35:10.238 --> 35:14.547
See, top right.
"Allison needs $40."

35:14.590 --> 35:18.899
<i>"I have asthma,
and I need a bus pass."</i>

35:18.942 --> 35:24.209
<i>"My eyes are failing,
and I need them to read."</i>

35:24.252 --> 35:28.213
<i>"I have back pain, and
I would like to hold my baby."</i>

35:28.256 --> 35:32.739
<i>Some of these prescriptions
are as low as $5.</i>

35:32.782 --> 35:34.784
We can help tell their story.

35:34.828 --> 35:38.832
These are not numbers or
statistics or reckless policy,

35:38.875 --> 35:40.225
they're just people.

35:40.268 --> 35:42.357
And when you see a person
in need, you help them.

35:42.401 --> 35:46.187
That's not a handout.
That's just humanity.

35:46.231 --> 35:49.190
<i>♪</i>

35:49.234 --> 35:55.022
<i>♪ This is only where
it begins ♪</i>

35:55.065 --> 35:58.330
<i>♪ Nobody knows how
the story ends ♪</i>

35:58.373 --> 36:00.549
<i>♪</i>

36:00.593 --> 36:03.248
<i>♪ Nobody knows how
the story ends ♪</i>

36:03.291 --> 36:05.685
<i>♪</i>

36:05.728 --> 36:08.949
[sighs]

36:08.992 --> 36:11.952
Hey.

36:11.995 --> 36:13.258
Rough day?

36:13.301 --> 36:15.390
Yeah, you know, work--
work is hard, and I--

36:15.434 --> 36:19.307
I, uh, just, uh--

36:19.351 --> 36:21.004
nothing, never mind.

36:21.048 --> 36:22.441
No, what?

36:22.484 --> 36:24.486
Nothing.
It's just--

36:24.530 --> 36:25.574
you know, it's us.

36:25.618 --> 36:27.794
It's--not us.
It's me, it's me.

36:27.837 --> 36:30.623
It's moving on stuff, and I'm--

36:30.666 --> 36:31.841
we can't talk about that, right?

36:31.885 --> 36:32.886
That's weird.

36:34.975 --> 36:39.414
No, it's--
it's not weird at all.

36:39.458 --> 36:41.242
Come on.
Spill it.

36:41.286 --> 36:44.027
- Really?
- Yeah, I'm a big boy.

36:44.071 --> 36:47.770
Uh, yeah, I don't--

36:47.814 --> 36:49.729
I don't know how
to be a single man, Martin.

36:49.772 --> 36:51.296
- [chuckles softly]
- I don't know what I'm doing.

36:51.339 --> 36:53.036
I'm--[chuckles]

36:53.080 --> 36:54.255
It's pathetic.

36:54.299 --> 36:55.952
I was terrible at it in my 20s.
You know.

36:55.996 --> 36:59.652
I'm terrible at it as
a single, middle-aged father.

36:59.695 --> 37:03.960
I'm--I'm just bad at it.
I'm a failed partner.

37:04.004 --> 37:05.440
- Come on.
- Well, it's true.

37:05.484 --> 37:06.876
Mm.

37:09.314 --> 37:12.012
That is my dating profile.

37:12.055 --> 37:15.798
Hard to tell, because nobody
swiped left, right, or center.

37:15.842 --> 37:17.191
Nobody.

37:17.235 --> 37:20.107
[chuckling] Um, uh...

37:20.150 --> 37:22.065
Iggy, your profile's set

37:22.109 --> 37:24.938
to only matches
over 90 years old.

37:24.981 --> 37:27.462
- I'm sorry, what?
- Yeah. [chuckles]

37:27.506 --> 37:29.682
- What?
- Buddy, yeah.

37:29.725 --> 37:32.598
I think if you just toggle that
and then switch that one.

37:32.641 --> 37:35.340
- Oh, my gosh.
- Boom.

37:35.383 --> 37:37.472
- Oh, my gosh.
- Wowza.

37:37.516 --> 37:39.039
<i>[phone chiming rapidly]</i>
[both chuckle]

37:39.082 --> 37:41.520
Oh.

37:41.563 --> 37:44.131
Holy moly.

37:44.174 --> 37:46.351
I'll see you in three days.

37:46.394 --> 37:49.267
Yeah, yeah, three days.
See you then.

37:49.310 --> 37:51.530
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

37:51.573 --> 37:53.967
[door opens and closes]

37:54.010 --> 37:55.447
[chuckles softly]

37:55.490 --> 38:01.975
<i>♪</i>

38:02.018 --> 38:03.629
Jesus, you going to
stand out here all night?

38:03.672 --> 38:05.805
I buzzed you up like
ten minutes ago.

38:10.418 --> 38:11.376
[door closes]

38:11.419 --> 38:12.594
<i>♪</i>

38:12.638 --> 38:14.466
Oh yeah, don't mind them.
They're not here.

38:14.509 --> 38:17.512
<i>♪</i>

38:17.556 --> 38:20.298
Yeah, so there are all
your clothes ready to go.

38:20.341 --> 38:22.909
<i>♪</i>

38:22.952 --> 38:25.259
Should I charge
you a storage fee?

38:25.303 --> 38:28.871
<i>♪</i>

38:28.915 --> 38:31.396
[sighs]

38:31.439 --> 38:38.446
<i>♪</i>

38:38.751 --> 38:41.188
[items clattering]

38:41.231 --> 38:42.929
You okay?

38:42.972 --> 38:44.496
[scoffs]

38:44.539 --> 38:46.367
Yeah, like you care.

38:46.411 --> 38:48.500
[wine trickling]

38:48.543 --> 38:53.287
<i>♪</i>

38:53.331 --> 38:57.117
You know,
there's been a change of plans.

38:57.160 --> 38:59.511
[lighter clicking]

38:59.554 --> 39:01.295
I think I might have
to crash here.

39:01.339 --> 39:04.516
<i>♪</i>

39:04.559 --> 39:07.257
Why?
What happened to your place?

39:07.301 --> 39:11.784
The truth is
you'd be doing me a favor,

39:11.827 --> 39:15.483
Really helping me out.
- [scoffs]

39:15.527 --> 39:17.616
If you let me stay here.

39:17.659 --> 39:20.270
<i>♪</i>

39:20.314 --> 39:23.317
Uh, yeah.

39:23.361 --> 39:25.624
Yeah, sure thing, sis.

39:25.667 --> 39:29.628
Just--I don't know...

39:29.671 --> 39:31.456
make yourself right at home.

39:31.499 --> 39:34.415
<i>♪</i>

39:34.459 --> 39:37.375
<i>[Phoebe Bridgers' "Punisher"]</i>

39:37.418 --> 39:40.290
<i>[soft indie folk music]</i>

39:40.334 --> 39:43.468
[indistinct chatter]

39:43.511 --> 39:44.643
<i>♪</i>

39:44.686 --> 39:49.212
<i>♪ When the speed kicks in</i>

39:49.256 --> 39:50.779
<i>♪</i>

39:52.825 --> 39:57.003
No, no.
I don't need Ben.

39:57.046 --> 39:58.657
I got this.

40:03.792 --> 40:04.880
[clears throat]

40:10.495 --> 40:12.018
<i>♪</i>

40:12.061 --> 40:14.977
<i>♪ The storybook tiles
on the roof ♪</i>

40:15.021 --> 40:17.371
<i>♪ Were too much</i>

40:17.415 --> 40:18.764
<i>♪</i>

40:18.807 --> 40:21.244
<i>♪ The drugstores
are open all night ♪</i>

40:21.288 --> 40:22.289
[sighs]

40:23.421 --> 40:24.857
"Was that a haiku?"

40:24.900 --> 40:26.989
No, it wasn't supposed to be.
- [laughs]

40:27.033 --> 40:28.382
No.

40:28.426 --> 40:29.514
<i>♪</i>

40:29.557 --> 40:30.819
No.
Uh, no, no.

40:30.863 --> 40:32.647
I don't want to use this.
Let me--

40:32.691 --> 40:35.476
<i>♪</i>

40:35.520 --> 40:38.827
Um...

40:38.871 --> 40:41.177
you've been there for me
when I needed you the most,

40:41.221 --> 40:43.789
and the truth is,

40:43.832 --> 40:47.227
I should have done this
a long time ago.

40:47.270 --> 40:49.272
So...

40:59.631 --> 41:01.110
Hamburger?

41:01.154 --> 41:04.287
Hamburgers?
No, no.

41:04.331 --> 41:05.941
Not hamburgers.

41:05.985 --> 41:07.552
Uh...

41:07.595 --> 41:08.944
no, not hamburgers.

41:08.988 --> 41:10.337
Uh...

41:10.380 --> 41:12.426
grateful we are, um...

41:12.470 --> 41:14.994
<i>♪ What if I told you</i>

41:15.037 --> 41:20.086
<i>♪ I feel like I know you</i>

41:20.129 --> 41:21.783
Friends.

41:21.827 --> 41:23.916
Friends.
- Friends.

41:23.959 --> 41:25.700
<i>♪ But we never met</i>

41:25.744 --> 41:26.832
Good.

41:26.875 --> 41:28.877
I got it.
Watch this.

41:28.921 --> 41:32.185
<i>♪ It's for the best</i>

41:32.228 --> 41:35.188
<i>♪ I can't open my mouth</i>

41:35.231 --> 41:38.321
<i>♪ And forget how to talk</i>

41:38.365 --> 41:39.497
- Same.
- Thank you.

41:39.540 --> 41:41.499
[laughs]

41:41.542 --> 41:43.631
<i>♪ 'Cause even if I could</i>

41:43.675 --> 41:46.329
<i>♪ Wouldn't know
where to start ♪</i>

41:46.373 --> 41:48.680
<i>♪ Wouldn't know
where to stop ♪</i>

42:20.755 --> 42:21.843
<i>[thunder rumbles]</i>
